## Row 7 — Exposed tools
<!-- baseline: artifact-exposed-tools-list, mcp-tools-list-metadata-completeness -->

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **Status** | {{ROW7_STATUS}} |
| **Evidence / pointer** | {{ROW7_EVIDENCE}} |
| **Owner** | {{ROW7_OWNER}} |
| **What we provide** | {{ROW7_RESPONSE}} |

<!-- guidance: What satisfies it: a named inventory of EVERY tool in the
server's code registration/dispatch registry. The registry is the SOURCE OF
TRUTH for the row set — it can be LARGER than the client/ESR-exposed
operation surface — and the live tools/list capture from Row 3 is the
CROSS-CHECK, never the row source. Tier by the privilege tiers the dispatch
table actually defines (e.g. read / propose / admin); never collapse or drop
a tier, and a refresh must never replace a fuller prior inventory with a
thinner subset — watch the numeric collision where the client-exposed
operation count equals one tier's count and the subset silently reads as the
whole registry. Include the administrative and conditional/approval-tier
tools even when the live capture omits them — omitting a tool the reviewer
then finds reachable reads as concealment. Close by naming BOTH counts: "the
registry defines N tools (tiers a/b/c); the client/ESR exposes M operations;
the delta is the X admin + Y conditional/approval tools that are
registry-resident but not client-listed because…" — the generator computes
this reconciliation from code, and a count mismatch here is a generator bug
to fix, not a row to fudge. -->

